orld of the Married, The}}\n[[Category:Joongang Tongyang Broadcasting Company television dramas]]\n[[Category:Korean-language television programs]]\n[[Category:2020s South Korean television series]]\n[[Category:2020 South Korean television series debuts]]\n<!-- [[Category:2020 South Korean television series endings]] -->\n[[Category:South Korean drama television series]]\n[[Category:Adultery in television]]\n[[Category:South Korean television series based on British television series]]\n", "name_user": "Seokgjin", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_World_of_the_Married"}
{"title_page": "Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n", "text_new": "{{short description|Dominican baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name        = Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n\n| image       = Encarnacion_2019.jpg\n| image_size  = 250\n| caption     = Encarnaci\u00f3n with the Yankees in 2019\n| team        = Chicago White Sox\n| number      = 23\n| position    = [[Designated hitter]] / [[First baseman]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1983|1|7}}\n| birth_place = [[La Romana, Dominican Republic]]\n| bats        = Right\n| throws      = Right\n| debutleague = MLB\n| debutdate   = June 24\n| debutyear   = 2005\n| debutteam   = Cincinnati Reds\n| statleague  = MLB\n| statyear    = 2019 season\n| stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value  = .263\n| stat2label  = [[Hit (baseball)|Hit]]s\n| stat2value  = 1,807\n| stat3label  = [[Home run]]s\n| stat3value  = 414\n| stat4label  = [[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n| stat4value  = 1,242\n| teams       = \n* [[Cincinnati Reds]] ({{mlby|2005}}\u2013{{mlby|2009}})\n* [[Toronto Blue Jays]] ({{mlby|2009}}\u2013{{mlby|2016}})\n* [[Cleveland Indians]] ({{mlby|2017}}\u2013{{mlby|2018}})\n* [[Seattle Mariners]] ({{mlby|2019}})\n* [[New York Yankees]] ({{mlby|2019}})\n| awards      = \n* 3\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2013]], [[2014 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2014]], [[2016 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2016]])\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual runs batted in leaders|AL RBI leader]] (2016)\n* [[2013 World Baseball Classic]] [[2013 World Baseball Classic#All\u2013WBC team|All-Tournament Team]]\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{bb|DR}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World Baseball Classic]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2013 World Baseball Classic|2013 San Francisco]] | [[Dominican Republic national baseball team|Team]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Edwin Elpidio Encarnaci\u00f3n''' (born January 7, 1983) is a [[Dominican Republic|Dominican]] [[professional baseball]] [[first baseman]] and [[designated hitter]] for the [[Chicago White Sox]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He previously played for the [[Cincinnati Reds]], [[Toronto Blue Jays]], [[Cleveland Indians]], [[Seattle Mariners]], and [[New York Yankees]]. Encarnaci\u00f3n is a three-time [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]].\n\n==Early life==\nEncarnaci\u00f3n was born in the Dominican Republic to Elpidio Encarnaci\u00f3n, a [[track and field]] coach, and Mireya Rivera. He is the third of three sons, including Richard and Julio, and four children, including younger sister, Evelin. Encarnaci\u00f3n also had twelve half-siblings via his father. Encarnaci\u00f3n split time as a high school student between his native country and [[Puerto Rico]] after his father took a job coaching at a Puerto Rican college. His Puerto Rican residence made him eligible for the [[Major League Baseball draft]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brunt|first1=Stephen|title=Edwin Encarnacion: On Home Turf - Sportsnet.ca|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/edwin-encarnacion-on-home-turf/|accessdate=October 5, 2016|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Cincinnati Reds===\nThe [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] selected Encarnaci\u00f3n in the ninth round of the [[2000 Major League Baseball draft]], and he signed with them. On June 15, 2001, the Rangers traded him and [[Rub\u00e9n Mateo]] to the [[Cincinnati Reds]] in exchange for [[pitcher]] [[Rob Bell (baseball)|Rob Bell]]. He made his [[Major League Baseball]] debut on June 24, 2005, and played in 69 games. He finished with a .232 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]], nine [[home run]]s, and 31 [[runs batted in]] (RBIs).<ref name=\"BR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/e/encared01.shtml|title=Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n Statistics and History|publisher=BaseballReference.com|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n.jpg|left|upright|thumb|Encarnaci\u00f3n with the [[Cincinnati Reds]]]]\nIn the 2006 season, Encarnaci\u00f3n played 117 games for the Reds, and batted .276 with 15 home runs and 72 RBIs.<ref name=\"BR\"/> Encarnaci\u00f3n won the National League Player of the Week award for the week of August 7\u201313. During the week, he led the league with 4 home runs and 24 total bases, batting .440 with eight RBIs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20060814&content_id=1609521&vkey=pr_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Edwin Encarnacion of the Reds named Bank of America Presents the National League Player of the Week|publisher=MLB.com|date=August 14, 2006|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Encarnaci\u00f3n started the year slowly, struggling to bat over .200. He was frequently benched in favor of [[Ryan Freel]], which gave [[Josh Hamilton]], who was attempting to resurrect his career after it was derailed by addiction to drugs and alcohol, more starts in center field. Encarnaci\u00f3n was benched again at one point by then [[Manager (baseball)|manager]] [[Jerry Narron]] for not running out a [[Batted ball|fly ball]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=2834516|title=Encarnacion benched for not running out pop fly|publisher=ESPN.com|date=April 12, 2007|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref> On May 10, 2007, Encarnaci\u00f3n was demoted to the Reds' [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] affiliate, the [[Louisville Bats]]. He was recalled to the Major Leagues on May 22, 2007. For the 2007 season, Encarnaci\u00f3n batted .289 with 16 home runs and 76 RBI.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\nIn 2008, Encarnaci\u00f3n set career highs in games played and home runs. He batted .251 in 146 games with 26 home runs and 68 RBIs, and also struck out 102 times, the first time he had struck out more than 100 times in his career.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\nFor the 2009 season, Encarnaci\u00f3n stated that he wanted to be more consistent as a hitter who did not try to hit home runs in every at bat: \"I want to try to stay more to the middle. Last year, I tried to pull too many balls and hit more homers. That's why my average went down. I will be more consistent as a hitter. I know I can do it. I've done it before. I know I can hit better than that and I just have to keep working\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090218&content_id=3844530&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Encarnacion out to shake \"homer-itis\"|last=Sheldon|first=Mark|publisher=MLB.com|date=February 18, 2009|accessdate=May 24, 2013}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n played in 43 games with the Reds in the 2009 season, batting just .209 with five home runs and 16 RBIs before being traded to Toronto.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\n===Toronto Blue Jays===\n\n====2009\u20132011====\n[[File:Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n on June 4, 2011.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Encarnaci\u00f3n in 2011]]\nEncarnaci\u00f3n, along with right-handed pitchers [[Josh Roenicke]] and [[Zach Stewart]], was traded to the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] for [[Scott Rolen]] on July 31, 2009. It was reported that then Blue Jays General Manager [[J. P. Ricciardi]] was only interested in acquiring Roenicke and Stewart, but Cincinnati would not accept the trade unless the Blue Jays also took on Encarnaci\u00f3n.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wap.mlb.com/tor/news/article/2013071753974696/|title=Blue jays' all-time Top 5 in-season trades|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|publisher=MLB.com|date=July 18, 2013|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n played in 42 games for the Blue Jays during the 2009 season, and batted .240 with eight home runs and 23 RBIs.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\nDuring the offseason, Encarnaci\u00f3n suffered first and second-degree burns to the forehead and the right side of his face when a rocket firecracker hit him in the jaw and exploded near his mouth. After initially being treated near his Dominican Republic home, Encarnacion was transferred to a Miami hospital. He was discharged less than two days after the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4790334|title=Firework explodes near infielder's face|last=Rojas|first=Enrique|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=January 2, 2010|accessdate=May 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nEncarnaci\u00f3n missed 30 games through April and May 2010 with a right arm injury, before returning on May 18, 2010. He hit a home run in his first at bat since the injury against the [[Minnesota Twins]]. On May 21, he had three home runs against the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]], homering in three straight at-bats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bluebirdbanter.com/2010/5/22/1482942/edwin-encarnacion-hits-3-home-runs|title=Edwin Encarnacion Hits 3 Home Runs, but Jays Lose|last=Dakers|first=Tom|publisher=BlueBirdBanter.com|date=May 22, 2010|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref> On June 20, after a loss to the Giants, Encarnacion was optioned to the Triple-A [[Las Vegas 51s]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bluebirdbanter.com/2010/6/20/1527405/blue-jays-option-3b-edwin|title=Blue Jays option 3B Edwin Encarnacion to AAA Las Vegas after today's game. No word yet on callup....|publisher=BlueBirdBanter.com|date=June 20, 2010|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref> However, in a surprise move, he was designated for assignment the next day by the Blue Jays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bluebirdbanter.com/2010/6/21/1528837/edwin-encarnacion-designated-for|title=Edwin Encarnacion Designated for Assignment|last=Dakers|first=Tom|publisher=BlueBirdBanter.com|date=June 21, 2010|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n was eventually assigned to Triple-A Las Vegas on June 23, 2010, but was later called up to the Blue Jays again on July 2, 2010 after a struggling performance by Encarnacion's replacement, [[Jarrett Hoffpauir]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100702&content_id=11835202&notebook_id=11841552&fext=.jsp&c_id=tor|title=Jays option Hoffpauir, call up Encarnacion|last=Bastain|first=Jordan|publisher=MLB.com|date=July 2, 2010|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref> He hit his 100th career home run against the [[Minnesota Twins]] on the last day of the season, and also became the Jays' 7th player of the 2010 season with 20 or more home runs. Encarnaci\u00f3n finished the 2010 season with a batting average of .244, 21 home runs and 51 RBI.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\nOn November 12, 2010, Encarnacion was claimed off waivers by the [[Oakland Athletics]]. On December 2, he was non-tendered by the Athletics, making him a free agent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oakland.athletics.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101202&content_id=16244938&vkey=news_oak&c_id=oak|title=A's part ways with Buck, Cust, Encarnacion|work=MLB.com|last=Lee|first=Jane|date=December 2, 2010|accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> On December 16, 2010, he signed a one-year deal with the Blue Jays worth $2.5 million, with a club option worth $3.5 million in 2012. He began the 2011 season playing third base for the Blue Jays and struggled offensively. His numbers improved significantly after he was moved to the designated hitter position. In a game against the [[Boston Red Sox]] on September 7, 2011, Encarnacion set a new career record for [[Double (baseball)|doubles]] in a single season with 34. On September 22, Encarnacion hit a walk-off home run off the Rogers Sportsnet One sign in the 12th inning against Angels rookie [[Garrett Richards]]. In 2011, Encarnaci\u00f3n batted .272 with 17 home runs and 55 RBIs.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\nOn October 31, 2011, the Jays picked up the $3.5 million club option for the 2012 season.<ref name= 'MLB.com'>{{cite web|title=Jays' options: Yes on Encarnacion, no on Rauch|date=October 31, 2011|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20111031&content_id=25851184&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor|work=MLB.com|accessdate=November 1, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111102121840/http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20111031&content_id=25851184&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor|archive-date=November 2, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====2012\u20132013====\nIn a game against the [[Seattle Mariners]] on April 28, 2012, Encarnaci\u00f3n hit his fourth career grand slam in the 8th inning leading the Blue Jays to a 7-0 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2012/04/28/encarnacions-grand-slam-paces-jays|title=Encarnacion's grand slam crushes M's|work=TorontoSun.com|last=Lankhof|first=Bill|date=April 28, 2012|accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> His grand slam marked the first time that Encarnaci\u00f3n held his arm out in his trademark \"chicken-wing\" fashion while rounding the bases.  This trademark would be known as the \"Parrot Walk\" which Edwin would do for every homerun he would hit from then on.  Fans would mimic it in the stands and even do a \"parrot\" flap of their arms.  It was so popular it generated t-shirts, hats and even stuffed parrots that fans could attach to their right arm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Baseball/MLB/Toronto/2013/06/22/20920941.html|title=Even Blue Jays' home run leader Edwin Encarnacion excited by Munenori Kawasaki bomb|last=Elliot|first=Bob|accessdate=August 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://bluejayhunter.com/2014/05/flashback-friday-birth-of-encarnacion-chicken-wing.html|title=Flashback Friday: The Birth of Edwin Encarnacion's Parrot Walk Home Run Trot|first=Ian|last=Hunter|date=May 30, 2014|accessdate=July 4, 2019|work=Blue Jay Hunter}}</ref>\n\nOn April 30, 2012, in a home game against the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]], Encarnaci\u00f3n hit the first home run off of starter [[Yu Darvish]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2012_04_30_texmlb_tormlb_1&mode=recap&c_id=tex|title=Darvish strikes out nine to improve to 4-0|work=MLB.com|last=Millson|first=Larry|date=May 1, 2012|accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> In an inter-league game against the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] on June 19, Encarnaci\u00f3n hit the last of three straight solo home runs by the Blue Jays, following [[Colby Rasmus]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Bautista]], the first time in the 2012 season that the Jays went back-to-back-to-back with home runs, and only the sixth time in franchise history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2012_06_19_tormlb_milmlb_1&mode=recap&c_id=tor | title=Rasmus, Bautista rally Blue Jays past Crew | publisher=MLB.com | date=June 20, 2012 | accessdate= June 20, 2012}}</ref> On July 12, Encarnaci\u00f3n signed a 3-year, $27 million contract extension with Toronto.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/dailypitch/post/2012/07/encarnacion-sticking-around-toronto-with-new-contract/1#.T__5JfVgFQ4|title=Encarnacion sticking around Toronto with new contract|last=Barzilai|first=Peter|date=July 12, 2012|accessdate=July 13, 2012|work=USA Today}}</ref> The deal included a $10 million club option for the 2016 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120712&content_id=34857644&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor|title=Blue Jays sign Edwin Encarnacion to three-year contract extension|last=Toman|first=Chris|date=July 12, 2012|accessdate=July 13, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718233015/http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120712&content_id=34857644&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor|archive-date=July 18, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn September 13, 2012, in a home game against the Seattle Mariners, Encarnaci\u00f3n hit his 40th home run of the season (off starter [[F\u00e9lix Hern\u00e1ndez]]), and recorded his 100th RBI of the season, marking the first time in his career that he had surpassed 40 home runs and 100 RBIs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2012_09_13_seamlb_tormlb_1&mode=recap&c_id=tor|title=Encarnacion belts No. 40 as Blue Jays pound King Felix|work=MLB.com|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|date=September 13, 2012|accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n was unanimously named by the Baseball Writers' Association of America (BBWAA) as the [[Neil MacCarl Award|Blue Jays Player of the Year]] on November 28, 2012. He also received the Most Improved Player award for the Jays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20121128&content_id=40445640&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor|title=Edwin Encarnacion named Blue Jays top player by BBWAA|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=November 28, 2012|accessdate=November 28, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121201150022/http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20121128&content_id=40445640&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor|archive-date=December 1, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n July 2013.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Encarnaci\u00f3n in 2013]]\nOn May 23, 2013, Encarnaci\u00f3n hit his fifth career grand slam to give the Blue Jays an 8\u20133 lead over the [[Baltimore Orioles]]. The Jays would win the game 12\u20136.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2013_05_23_balmlb_tormlb_1&mode=recap_home&c_id=tor|title=Encarnacion's slam punctuates batting showcase|last=Peaslee|first=Evan|publisher=MLB.com|date=May 24, 2013|accessdate=May 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn July 6, 2013, Encarnaci\u00f3n was named to his first all-star game as a reserve designated hitter for the American League. Encarnaci\u00f3n was one of four Blue Jays to be named, the others being Jos\u00e9 Bautista, [[Brett Cecil]], and [[Steve Delabar]]. Up to the All-Star break, Encarnaci\u00f3n posted a triple-slash of .264/.353/.532 with 25 home runs and 72 RBIs. In the All-Star Game, Encarnaci\u00f3n entered as a pinch-hitter for [[David Ortiz]] in the seventh inning, and finished the game 0\u20132. In a game against the [[Houston Astros]] on July 26, 2013, Encarnaci\u00f3n became only the second Blue Jay in franchise history to hit two home runs in one inning, joining [[Joe Carter]] who did so on October 3, 1993 \u2013 tying the Major League record for most home runs in an inning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=330726114&teams=houston-astros-vs-toronto-blue-jays|title=Jays' Edwin Encarnacion hits 2 HRs in 8-run 7th inning uprising|date=July 26, 2013|publisher=espn.com|accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/recbooks/rb_hr10.shtml|title=Most Home Run in an Inning Records|date=|publisher=baseball-almanac.com|accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref> Leading off the 7th inning behind at 6\u20134, Encarnaci\u00f3n hit a solo home run and would later hit his sixth career grand slam, receiving a [[curtain call]] afterwards as the Blue Jays would score 8 runs in the inning and lead 12\u20136.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2013_07_26_houmlb_tormlb_1&mode=recap_home&c_id=tor|title=Encarnacion, Reyes power Blue Jays' outburst|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|publisher=MLB.com|date=July 27, 2013|accessdate=July 27, 2013}}</ref> He was named the American League Player of the Week on July 29, after batting .520 with three doubles, two home runs, and eight RBIs over the prior week.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/baseball/blue-jays-edwin-encarnacion-named-al-player-of-the-week/article13482931/|title=Blue Jays' Edwin Encarnacion named AL player of the week|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]|date=July 29, 2013|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n hit his 30th home run of the season on August 7, 2013, against the Seattle Mariners. In doing so, he recorded back-to-back 30 home run seasons for the first time in his career. Playing against the [[Kansas City Royals]] on August 31, 2013, Encarnaci\u00f3n recorded his 1,000th career hit, a single off Kansas City starter [[Jeremy Guthrie]]. On September 2, he reached 100 RBIs for the second consecutive season on a two-run home run against [[Brandon McCarthy]] of the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]]. He spent time on the bench in mid September with a wrist injury, but made a brief comeback before being placed on the disabled list on September 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/bluejays/2013/09/17/blue_jays_shut_down_edwin_encarnacion_and_brett_cecil.html|title=Blue Jays shut down Edwin Encarnacion and Brett Cecil|last=Kennedy|first=Brendan|publisher=thestar.com|date=September 17, 2013|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref> He underwent successful surgery on September 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/jays-encarnacion-has-successful-wrist-surgery/|title=Jays' Encarnacion has successful wrist surgery|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]|date=September 19, 2013|accessdate=September 19, 2013}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n finished the 2013 season with a .272 average, 36 home runs, and 104 RBIs. He finished with more walks than strikeouts for the first time in his career, with 82 and 62 respectively.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\n====2014\u20132016====\nEncarnaci\u00f3n hit his 200th career home run on May 8, 2014, against [[A. J. Burnett]] of the [[Philadelphia Phillies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article/mlb/helping-to-key-blue-jays-offence-edwin-encarnacion-hits-200th-hr?ymd=20140508&content_id=74820452&vkey=news_mlb|title=Helping to key offence, Encarnacion hits 200th HR|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=May 8, 2014|accessdate=May 8, 2014}}</ref> On May 12, he was named the American League Player of the Week for May 5\u201311, when he recorded a league-leading four home runs and 10 RBIs, and batted .321.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=451982|title=Blue Jays' Encarnacion named AL Player of the Week|work=TSN.ca|date=May 12, 2014|accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n continued his hot hitting in May by becoming the first player in Blue Jays franchise history to have 4 multi home run games in a month, and the first player in the majors to do so since [[Troy Tulowitzki]] in September 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?c_id=tor&gid=2014_05_21_tormlb_bosmlb_1&mode=recap_away&partnerId=as_mlb_20140522_24425944|title=Encarnacion's 2nd straight 2-HR game lifts Blue Jays|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=May 21, 2014|accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> On May 26 he established a new club record for home runs in May by hitting his 13th off of [[\u00c1lex Colom\u00e9]] of the [[Tampa Bay Rays]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2014_05_26_tbamlb_tormlb_1&mode=recap_home&c_id=tor|title=Blue Jays rout Rays with 16 hits, three homers|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=May 26, 2014|accessdate=May 26, 2014}}</ref> The following day, Encarnaci\u00f3n tied the team record for home runs in any month of the season, when he hit his 14th to help the Blue Jays extend their winning streak to 8 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article/mlb/blue-jays-first-baseman-edwin-encarnacion-ties-club-record-with-14th-homer-in-a-month?ymd=20140527&content_id=77067720&vkey=news_mlb|title=Edwin ties club record with 14th homer in a month|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=May 27, 2014|accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn May 29, in a home game against the [[Kansas City Royals]], Encarnaci\u00f3n hit two home runs for a total of 18 on the season and 16 in the month of May, giving him the Blue Jays franchise record for home runs in any month of the regular season. He also tied [[Mickey Mantle]] for the American League record for home runs in May.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article/mlb/blue-jays-slugger-edwin-encarnacion-ties-mickey-mantle-for-most-american-league-homers-hit-in-may?ymd=20140529&content_id=77398728&vkey=news_mlb|title=Encarnacion ties Mantle for most AL homers in May|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=May 29, 2014|accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref> He was unanimously selected as the Blue Jays Player of the Month by the Toronto chapter of the BBWAA on June 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20140602&content_id=77864090&vkey=pr_tor&c_id=tor|title=Encarnacion named Honda Player of the Month|work=MLB.com|date=June 2, 2014|accessdate=June 2, 2014}}</ref> A day later he was named the [[Major League Baseball Player of the Month|AL Player of the Month]] of May by MLB.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20140603&content_id=78018698&vkey=pr_mlb&c_id=mlb|title=Edwin Encarnacion of the Toronto Blue Jays named the American League Player of the Month for May|work=MLB.com|date=June 3, 2014|accessdate=June 3, 2014}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n hit two 3-run home runs in a win over the Cincinnati Reds on June 20. His 6 RBIs were a key contribution in helping the Blue Jays to their second-largest comeback victory in franchise history, being down 8\u20130 after the second inning and going on to win 14\u20139.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2014_06_20_tormlb_cinmlb_1&mode=recap_away&c_id=tor|title=Encarnacion leads Blue Jays' epic comeback|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=June 20, 2014|accessdate=June 20, 2014}}</ref> In total for 2014, Encarnaci\u00f3n batted .268 with 34 home runs and 98 RBIs.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\nOn June 30, 2015, Encarnaci\u00f3n earned 10-and-5 rights by having at least 10 years of service time in the big-leagues, with the last 5 being on the same team. These rights give Encarnaci\u00f3n the ability to veto any trade he would be involved in.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/against-the-odds-encarnacion-hits-special-milestone/|title=Against the odds, Encarnacion hits special milestone|last=Davidi|first=Shi|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=June 30, 2015|accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> He joined fellow Blue Jay Jos\u00e9 Bautista on the list of active players to hold this distinction.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.vice.com/en_us/article/allowing-bautista-encarnacion-to-acquire-veto-rights-shows-blue-jays-have-no-desire-to-trade-them|title=Allowing Bautista, Encarnacion to acquire veto rights shows the Blue Jays have no desire to trade them|work=sports.vice.com|date=June 11, 2015|accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n hit his 250th career home run on August 6, in a 9\u20133 win over the Minnesota Twins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/baseball/mlb/edwin-encarnacion-blue-jays-bats-make-twins-pay-in-series-finale-1.3182242|title=Edwin Encarnacion, Blue Jays' bats make Twins pay in series finale|last=Whyno|first=Stephen|work=cbc.ca|date=August 6, 2015|accessdate=August 6, 2015}}</ref> In an 8\u20135 win over the Philadelphia Phillies on August 18, Encarnaci\u00f3n surpassed [[Jesse Barfield]] on the Blue Jays' all-time home run list, hitting his 180th home run with the franchise. He also extended his hitting streak to a career-high 15 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fantasynews.cbssports.com/fantasybaseball/update/25273999/blue-jays-edwin-encarnacion-hits-in-15th-straight|title=Blue Jays' Edwin Encarnacion hits in 15th straight|last=Krest|first=Shawn|work=fantasynews.cbssports.com|date=August 18, 2015|accessdate=August 18, 2015}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n extended his hitting streak to 24 games on August 29, hitting 3 home runs against the [[Detroit Tigers]], including his third grand slam of the season, and tied [[Roy Howell]]'s franchise record with nine RBIs in a single game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/146101440|title=Encarnacion homers three times, extends hit streak to 24|last=Ross|first=Jamie|work=MLB.com|date=August 29, 2015|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/baseball/mlb/edwin-encarnacion-hits-3-homers-in-blue-jays-rout-of-tigers-1.3208608|title=Edwin Encarnacion hits 3 homers in Blue Jays' rout of Tigers|last=Whyno|first=Stephen|work=cbc.ca|date=August 29, 2015|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref> The following day, Encarnaci\u00f3n broke the franchise record for RBIs in a single month, when he hit a solo home run to give him 35 RBIs in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/146275574|title=Encore-nacion: Homer extends streak to 25|last=Ross|first=Jamie|work=MLB.com|date=August 30, 2015|accessdate=August 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-encarnacion-extend-hitting-streak-sets-new-record/|title=Blue Jays' Encarnacion extends hitting streak, sets new record|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=August 30, 2015|accessdate=August 30, 2015}}</ref> He was named the American League Player of the Week on August 31, after batting .391 with 6 home runs and 17 RBIs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/146492008|title=Edwin Encarnacion of the Toronto Blue Jays named American League Player of the Week|work=MLB.com|date=August 31, 2015|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> On September 2, Encarnaci\u00f3n won the American League Player of the Month award for the second time in his career, after batting .407 with 11 home runs and 35 RBIs in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MLB/status/639173111691083776|title=MLB on Twitter|work=Twitter|date=September 2, 2015|accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref> \n\nHe finished the 2015 regular season with a .277 batting average, 39 home runs, and 111 RBIs.<ref name=\"BR\"/> Encarnaci\u00f3n played in all 5 games of the [[2015 American League Division Series]], and batted .333 with one home run and 3 RBIs. In the [[2015 American League Championship Series|American League Championship Series]], he hit .227 with two RBIs in 6 games.<ref name=\"BR\"/> On October 27, Encarnaci\u00f3n underwent successful [[Athletic pubalgia|sports hernia]] surgery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-slugger-encarnacion-undergoes-sports-hernia-surgery/|title=Blue Jays slugger Encarnacion undergoes sports hernia surgery|last=Davidi|first=Shi|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=October 27, 2015|accessdate=October 27, 2015}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n's $10 million option for 2016 was exercised by the Blue Jays on November 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-exercise-options-on-bautista-dickey-encarnacion/|title=Blue Jays exercise options on Bautista, Dickey, Encarnacion|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=November 3, 2015|accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n 2016 Opening Day.jpg|thumb|left|Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n in 2016 Opening Day]]\nPrior to 2016 spring training, Encarnaci\u00f3n set an Opening Day deadline to negotiate a contract extension with the Blue Jays. He suffered an oblique injury early in the spring, and as a result did not participate in any Major League games. In addition, contract extension negotiations ended early, when both sides could not agree on the terms of the contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/bluejays/2016/04/04/blue-jays-edwin-encarnacion-end-extension-talks.html|title=Blue Jays, Edwin Encarnacion end extension talks|last=Kennedy|first=Brendan|work=thestar.com|date=April 4, 2016|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref> On April 26, Encarnaci\u00f3n hit his 200th home run as a member of the Blue Jays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/encarnacion-continues-ascent-blue-jays-home-run-ranks/|title=Encarnacion continues ascent of Blue Jays' home run ranks|last=Davidi|first=Shi|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=April 27, 2016|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n hit his fourth walk-off home run as a Blue Jay on June 10, defeating the Baltimore Orioles 4\u20133 in the tenth inning. In doing so, he became the Blue Jays all-time leader in walk-off home runs as well as the eighth player in franchise history to reach 600 RBI.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/encarnacion-gives-blue-jays-another-moment-cherish/|title=Encarnacion gives Blue Jays another moment to cherish|last=Blair|first=Jeff|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=June 10, 2016|accessdate=June 10, 2016}}</ref> In the first inning of a game on [[Canada Day|July 1]], Encarnaci\u00f3n was ejected by home plate umpire [[Vic Carapazza]] for arguing balls and strikes. He made contact with Carapazza after being ejected, and on July 3, was given a one-game suspension.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-encarnacion-suspended-one-game-bumping-umpire/|title=Blue Jays' Encarnacion suspended one game for bumping umpire|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=July 3, 2016|accessdate=July 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/teams/toronto-blue-jays/blue-jays-encarnacion-drops-appeal-serves-one-game-suspension/|title=Blue Jays' Encarnacion drops appeal, serves one-game suspension|last=Ashbourne|first=Nick|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=July 10, 2016|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> On August 12, Encarnaci\u00f3n hit the 300th home run of his career, joining [[Joe Carter]], [[Carlos Delgado]], and teammate Jos\u00e9 Bautista as the only players to hit their 300th home run with the Blue Jays franchise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/195237516/edwin-encarnacion-hits-his-300th-career-hr/|title=Encarnacion clubs his 300th career home run|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=August 12, 2016|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n recorded his 100th RBI of the season in a 12\u20136 win over the [[New York Yankees]] on August 16, becoming the first player to reach the milestone in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/196060940/edwin-encarnacion-first-to-100-rbis/|title=3-RBI night puts Encarnacion 1st to 100 RBIs|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=August 17, 2016|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref> On September 16, he hit his 40th home run of the season, and joined Jos\u00e9 Bautista and Carlos Delgado as the only Blue Jays with multiple 40-homer seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/tulowitzki-encarnacion-slug-blue-jays-win-angels/|title=Tulowitzki, Encarnacion slug Blue Jays to win over Angels|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=September 17, 2016|accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the eleventh inning of the [[2016 American League Wild Card Game|2016 Wild Card game]], Encarnaci\u00f3n hit a walk-off, three-run home run to give the Blue Jays a 5\u20132 victory and send them to the [[2016 American League Division Series|American League Division Series]] to face the Texas Rangers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-defeat-orioles-al-wild-card-game/|title=Encarnacion walk-off lifts Blue Jays over Orioles in AL wild-card game|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=October 4, 2016|accessdate=October 4, 2016}}</ref> On November 7, the Blue Jays extended a $17.2 million qualifying offer to Encarnaci\u00f3n,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-extend-qualifying-offers-encarnacion-bautista/|title=Blue Jays extend qualifying offers to Encarnacion, Bautista|last=Davidi|first=Shi|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=November 7, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2016}}</ref> which he declined on November 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/208848218/edwin-encarnacion-jose-bautista-free-agents/|title=Encarnacion, Bautista reject qualifying offers|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=November 14, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Cleveland Indians===\n[[File:Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n 2017 vs. Orioles.jpg|thumb|Encarnaci\u00f3n with the Indians]]\nOn January 5, 2017, Encarnaci\u00f3n signed a three-year contract with the [[Cleveland Indians]] worth $60 million.<ref>{{cite web|title=Indians sign free agent Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n to a three-year contract|url=http://m.indians.mlb.com/news/article/212729276/indians-introduce-edwin-encarnacion/|accessdate=January 5, 2017 |first=Jordan |last=Bastian |work=mlb.com |date=January 5, 2017}}</ref> The deal included a club option for the 2020 season worth an additional $25 million, with a $5 million [[buyout]] clause.\nOn Opening Day, he hit a home run against the Texas Rangers. On July 25, 2017, in the first game of a series against the [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim]], Encarnaci\u00f3n hit a walk-off grand slam in the bottom of the 11th inning, winning the game 11-7 for the Indians. In his first season with the Indians, he hit .258 with 38 home runs and 107 RBIs. He also drew a career high 104 walks.\n\nOn August 12, 2018, Encarnaci\u00f3n was placed on the disabled list with a hand contusion, his second stint on the disabled list in the season.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.mlb.com/indians/news/edwin-encarnacion-goes-on-disabled-list/c-289893662 | title=Hand contusion lands Edwin on disabled list}}</ref> He finished the season with 32 home runs and 107 RBIs, his seventh consecutive season of over 30 home runs and his fourth consecutive season of 100 or more RBIs. However, he batted .246.\n\n===Seattle Mariners===\nOn December 13, 2018, the Indians traded Encarnaci\u00f3n to the [[Seattle Mariners]] in a three-team trade with the [[Tampa Bay Rays]] which sent [[Carlos Santana (baseball)|Carlos Santana]] to the Indians, with the Indians also acquiring [[Jake Bauers]] from the Rays, with the Rays getting [[Yandy D\u00edaz]] and [[Cole Sulser]].<ref>{{cite web|last=|first=|url=https://marinersblog.mlblogs.com/mariners-acquire-1b-dh-edwin-encarnaci%C3%B3n-and-compensatory-round-b-pick-from-indians-7b50a5260876?sf96357322=1|title=Mariners Acquire 1B/DH Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n and Compensatory Round B Pick from Indians |publisher=mariners.mlb.com |date=December 13, 2018 |accessdate=December 13, 2018}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n hit his first home run as a member of the Seattle Mariners on March 28, 2019. In 65 games with the Mariners through mid-June, Encarnaci\u00f3n batted .241 with 21 home runs and 49 RBIs.\n\n===New York Yankees===\n[[File:Encarnacion 2019.jpg|thumb|Encarnaci\u00f3n with the Yankees in 2019]]\nOn June 15, 2019, the Mariners traded Encarnaci\u00f3n to the [[New York Yankees]] in exchange for minor league pitcher Juan Then and cash considerations.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/edwin-encarnacion-trade-yankees |title=Yanks acquire Encarnacion from M's |first=Russell |last=Dorsey |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=June 16, 2019 |accessdate=June 16, 2019}}</ref> On August 3, Encarnaci\u00f3n was hit by a pitch; he left the game with a fractured right wrist, and was placed on the 10-day injured list later that day. On October 31, 2019, the New York Yankees announced they would not be exercising their club option for Encarnaci\u00f3n for 2020, allowing him to enter the 2019-2020 free agent market.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/players/playerpage/392294/edwin-encarnacion |title = Edwin Encarnacion, DH, New York Yankees}}</ref>\n\n===Chicago White Sox=== \nOn January 9, 2020, Encarnacion signed a 1-year deal with the White Sox.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/edwin-encarnacion-signs-with-white-sox|title=White Sox announce deal with Encarnacion|date=January 9, 2020|accessdate=January 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Baseball|Dominican Republic}}\n*[[List of Major League Baseball career home run leaders]]\n*[[List of Toronto Blue Jays home run leaders]]\n*[[List of Toronto Blue Jays team records]]\n*[[Major League Baseball Player of the Week Award]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=429665|espn=5904|br=e/encared01|fangraphs=2151|brm=encarn001edw|retro=E/Pencae001}}\n* {{twitter}}\n* {{instagram|encadwin|Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n}}\n\n{{AL RBI champions}}\n{{Dominican Republic roster 2013 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{2013 World Baseball Classic All WBC Team}}\n{{Chicago White Sox roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Encarnacion, Edwin}}\n\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:\u00c1guilas Cibae\u00f1as players]]\n[[Category:All-Star Futures Game players]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:American League RBI champions]]\n[[Category:Billings Mustangs players]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Chattanooga Lookouts players]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Reds players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Indians players]]\n[[Category:Dayton Dragons players]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic expatriate baseball players in Canada]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic expatriate baseball players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic expatriates in Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Dunedin Blue Jays players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Las Vegas 51s players]]\n[[Category:Louisville Bats players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball designated hitters]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball first basemen]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball players from the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball third basemen]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees players]]\n[[Category:People from Caguas, Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:People from La Romana, Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Potomac Cannons players]]\n[[Category:Savannah Sand Gnats players]]\n[[Category:Seattle Mariners players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Blue Jays players]]\n[[Category:2013 World Baseball Classic players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Dominican baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name        = Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n\n| image       = File:Edwin Encarnacion Mariners.jpg\n| image_size  = 250\n| caption     = Encarnaci\u00f3n with the Mariners in 2019\n| team        = Chicago White Sox\n| number      = 23\n| position    = [[Designated hitter]] / [[First baseman]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1983|1|7}}\n| birth_place = [[La Romana, Dominican Republic]]\n| bats        = Right\n| throws      = Right\n| debutleague = MLB\n| debutdate   = June 24\n| debutyear   = 2005\n| debutteam   = Cincinnati Reds\n| statleague  = MLB\n| statyear    = 2019 season\n| stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value  = .263\n| stat2label  = [[Hit (baseball)|Hit]]s\n| stat2value  = 1,807\n| stat3label  = [[Home run]]s\n| stat3value  = 414\n| stat4label  = [[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n| stat4value  = 1,242\n| teams       = \n* [[Cincinnati Reds]] ({{mlby|2005}}\u2013{{mlby|2009}})\n* [[Toronto Blue Jays]] ({{mlby|2009}}\u2013{{mlby|2016}})\n* [[Cleveland Indians]] ({{mlby|2017}}\u2013{{mlby|2018}})\n* [[Seattle Mariners]] ({{mlby|2019}})\n* [[New York Yankees]] ({{mlby|2019}})\n| awards      = \n* 3\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2013]], [[2014 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2014]], [[2016 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2016]])\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual runs batted in leaders|AL RBI leader]] (2016)\n* [[2013 World Baseball Classic]] [[2013 World Baseball Classic#All\u2013WBC team|All-Tournament Team]]\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{bb|DR}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World Baseball Classic]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2013 World Baseball Classic|2013 San Francisco]] | [[Dominican Republic national baseball team|Team]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Edwin Elpidio Encarnaci\u00f3n''' (born January 7, 1983) is a [[Dominican Republic|Dominican]] [[professional baseball]] [[first baseman]] and [[designated hitter]] for the [[Chicago White Sox]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He previously played for the [[Cincinnati Reds]], [[Toronto Blue Jays]], [[Cleveland Indians]], [[Seattle Mariners]], and [[New York Yankees]]. Encarnaci\u00f3n is a three-time [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]].\n\n==Early life==\nEncarnaci\u00f3n was born in the Dominican Republic to Elpidio Encarnaci\u00f3n, a [[track and field]] coach, and Mireya Rivera. He is the third of three sons, including Richard and Julio, and four children, including younger sister, Evelin. Encarnaci\u00f3n also had twelve half-siblings via his father. Encarnaci\u00f3n split time as a high school student between his native country and [[Puerto Rico]] after his father took a job coaching at a Puerto Rican college. His Puerto Rican residence made him eligible for the [[Major League Baseball draft]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brunt|first1=Stephen|title=Edwin Encarnacion: On Home Turf - Sportsnet.ca|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/edwin-encarnacion-on-home-turf/|accessdate=October 5, 2016|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Cincinnati Reds===\nThe [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] selected Encarnaci\u00f3n in the ninth round of the [[2000 Major League Baseball draft]], and he signed with them. On June 15, 2001, the Rangers traded him and [[Rub\u00e9n Mateo]] to the [[Cincinnati Reds]] in exchange for [[pitcher]] [[Rob Bell (baseball)|Rob Bell]]. He made his [[Major League Baseball]] debut on June 24, 2005, and played in 69 games. He finished with a .232 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]], nine [[home run]]s, and 31 [[runs batted in]] (RBIs).<ref name=\"BR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/e/encared01.shtml|title=Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n Statistics and History|publisher=BaseballReference.com|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n.jpg|left|upright|thumb|Encarnaci\u00f3n with the [[Cincinnati Reds]]]]\nIn the 2006 season, Encarnaci\u00f3n played 117 games for the Reds, and batted .276 with 15 home runs and 72 RBIs.<ref name=\"BR\"/> Encarnaci\u00f3n won the National League Player of the Week award for the week of August 7\u201313. During the week, he led the league with 4 home runs and 24 total bases, batting .440 with eight RBIs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20060814&content_id=1609521&vkey=pr_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Edwin Encarnacion of the Reds named Bank of America Presents the National League Player of the Week|publisher=MLB.com|date=August 14, 2006|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Encarnaci\u00f3n started the year slowly, struggling to bat over .200. He was frequently benched in favor of [[Ryan Freel]], which gave [[Josh Hamilton]], who was attempting to resurrect his career after it was derailed by addiction to drugs and alcohol, more starts in center field. Encarnaci\u00f3n was benched again at one point by then [[Manager (baseball)|manager]] [[Jerry Narron]] for not running out a [[Batted ball|fly ball]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=2834516|title=Encarnacion benched for not running out pop fly|publisher=ESPN.com|date=April 12, 2007|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref> On May 10, 2007, Encarnaci\u00f3n was demoted to the Reds' [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] affiliate, the [[Louisville Bats]]. He was recalled to the Major Leagues on May 22, 2007. For the 2007 season, Encarnaci\u00f3n batted .289 with 16 home runs and 76 RBI.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\nIn 2008, Encarnaci\u00f3n set career highs in games played and home runs. He batted .251 in 146 games with 26 home runs and 68 RBIs, and also struck out 102 times, the first time he had struck out more than 100 times in his career.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\nFor the 2009 season, Encarnaci\u00f3n stated that he wanted to be more consistent as a hitter who did not try to hit home runs in every at bat: \"I want to try to stay more to the middle. Last year, I tried to pull too many balls and hit more homers. That's why my average went down. I will be more consistent as a hitter. I know I can do it. I've done it before. I know I can hit better than that and I just have to keep working\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090218&content_id=3844530&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Encarnacion out to shake \"homer-itis\"|last=Sheldon|first=Mark|publisher=MLB.com|date=February 18, 2009|accessdate=May 24, 2013}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n played in 43 games with the Reds in the 2009 season, batting just .209 with five home runs and 16 RBIs before being traded to Toronto.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\n===Toronto Blue Jays===\n\n====2009\u20132011====\n[[File:Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n on June 4, 2011.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Encarnaci\u00f3n in 2011]]\nEncarnaci\u00f3n, along with right-handed pitchers [[Josh Roenicke]] and [[Zach Stewart]], was traded to the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] for [[Scott Rolen]] on July 31, 2009. It was reported that then Blue Jays General Manager [[J. P. Ricciardi]] was only interested in acquiring Roenicke and Stewart, but Cincinnati would not accept the trade unless the Blue Jays also took on Encarnaci\u00f3n.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wap.mlb.com/tor/news/article/2013071753974696/|title=Blue jays' all-time Top 5 in-season trades|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|publisher=MLB.com|date=July 18, 2013|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n played in 42 games for the Blue Jays during the 2009 season, and batted .240 with eight home runs and 23 RBIs.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\nDuring the offseason, Encarnaci\u00f3n suffered first and second-degree burns to the forehead and the right side of his face when a rocket firecracker hit him in the jaw and exploded near his mouth. After initially being treated near his Dominican Republic home, Encarnacion was transferred to a Miami hospital. He was discharged less than two days after the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4790334|title=Firework explodes near infielder's face|last=Rojas|first=Enrique|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=January 2, 2010|accessdate=May 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nEncarnaci\u00f3n missed 30 games through April and May 2010 with a right arm injury, before returning on May 18, 2010. He hit a home run in his first at bat since the injury against the [[Minnesota Twins]]. On May 21, he had three home runs against the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]], homering in three straight at-bats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bluebirdbanter.com/2010/5/22/1482942/edwin-encarnacion-hits-3-home-runs|title=Edwin Encarnacion Hits 3 Home Runs, but Jays Lose|last=Dakers|first=Tom|publisher=BlueBirdBanter.com|date=May 22, 2010|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref> On June 20, after a loss to the Giants, Encarnacion was optioned to the Triple-A [[Las Vegas 51s]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bluebirdbanter.com/2010/6/20/1527405/blue-jays-option-3b-edwin|title=Blue Jays option 3B Edwin Encarnacion to AAA Las Vegas after today's game. No word yet on callup....|publisher=BlueBirdBanter.com|date=June 20, 2010|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref> However, in a surprise move, he was designated for assignment the next day by the Blue Jays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bluebirdbanter.com/2010/6/21/1528837/edwin-encarnacion-designated-for|title=Edwin Encarnacion Designated for Assignment|last=Dakers|first=Tom|publisher=BlueBirdBanter.com|date=June 21, 2010|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n was eventually assigned to Triple-A Las Vegas on June 23, 2010, but was later called up to the Blue Jays again on July 2, 2010 after a struggling performance by Encarnacion's replacement, [[Jarrett Hoffpauir]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100702&content_id=11835202&notebook_id=11841552&fext=.jsp&c_id=tor|title=Jays option Hoffpauir, call up Encarnacion|last=Bastain|first=Jordan|publisher=MLB.com|date=July 2, 2010|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref> He hit his 100th career home run against the [[Minnesota Twins]] on the last day of the season, and also became the Jays' 7th player of the 2010 season with 20 or more home runs. Encarnaci\u00f3n finished the 2010 season with a batting average of .244, 21 home runs and 51 RBI.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\nOn November 12, 2010, Encarnacion was claimed off waivers by the [[Oakland Athletics]]. On December 2, he was non-tendered by the Athletics, making him a free agent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oakland.athletics.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101202&content_id=16244938&vkey=news_oak&c_id=oak|title=A's part ways with Buck, Cust, Encarnacion|work=MLB.com|last=Lee|first=Jane|date=December 2, 2010|accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> On December 16, 2010, he signed a one-year deal with the Blue Jays worth $2.5 million, with a club option worth $3.5 million in 2012. He began the 2011 season playing third base for the Blue Jays and struggled offensively. His numbers improved significantly after he was moved to the designated hitter position. In a game against the [[Boston Red Sox]] on September 7, 2011, Encarnacion set a new career record for [[Double (baseball)|doubles]] in a single season with 34. On September 22, Encarnacion hit a walk-off home run off the Rogers Sportsnet One sign in the 12th inning against Angels rookie [[Garrett Richards]]. In 2011, Encarnaci\u00f3n batted .272 with 17 home runs and 55 RBIs.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\nOn October 31, 2011, the Jays picked up the $3.5 million club option for the 2012 season.<ref name= 'MLB.com'>{{cite web|title=Jays' options: Yes on Encarnacion, no on Rauch|date=October 31, 2011|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20111031&content_id=25851184&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor|work=MLB.com|accessdate=November 1, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111102121840/http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20111031&content_id=25851184&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor|archive-date=November 2, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====2012\u20132013====\nIn a game against the [[Seattle Mariners]] on April 28, 2012, Encarnaci\u00f3n hit his fourth career grand slam in the 8th inning leading the Blue Jays to a 7-0 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2012/04/28/encarnacions-grand-slam-paces-jays|title=Encarnacion's grand slam crushes M's|work=TorontoSun.com|last=Lankhof|first=Bill|date=April 28, 2012|accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> His grand slam marked the first time that Encarnaci\u00f3n held his arm out in his trademark \"chicken-wing\" fashion while rounding the bases.  This trademark would be known as the \"Parrot Walk\" which Edwin would do for every homerun he would hit from then on.  Fans would mimic it in the stands and even do a \"parrot\" flap of their arms.  It was so popular it generated t-shirts, hats and even stuffed parrots that fans could attach to their right arm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Baseball/MLB/Toronto/2013/06/22/20920941.html|title=Even Blue Jays' home run leader Edwin Encarnacion excited by Munenori Kawasaki bomb|last=Elliot|first=Bob|accessdate=August 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://bluejayhunter.com/2014/05/flashback-friday-birth-of-encarnacion-chicken-wing.html|title=Flashback Friday: The Birth of Edwin Encarnacion's Parrot Walk Home Run Trot|first=Ian|last=Hunter|date=May 30, 2014|accessdate=July 4, 2019|work=Blue Jay Hunter}}</ref>\n\nOn April 30, 2012, in a home game against the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]], Encarnaci\u00f3n hit the first home run off of starter [[Yu Darvish]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2012_04_30_texmlb_tormlb_1&mode=recap&c_id=tex|title=Darvish strikes out nine to improve to 4-0|work=MLB.com|last=Millson|first=Larry|date=May 1, 2012|accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> In an inter-league game against the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] on June 19, Encarnaci\u00f3n hit the last of three straight solo home runs by the Blue Jays, following [[Colby Rasmus]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Bautista]], the first time in the 2012 season that the Jays went back-to-back-to-back with home runs, and only the sixth time in franchise history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2012_06_19_tormlb_milmlb_1&mode=recap&c_id=tor | title=Rasmus, Bautista rally Blue Jays past Crew | publisher=MLB.com | date=June 20, 2012 | accessdate= June 20, 2012}}</ref> On July 12, Encarnaci\u00f3n signed a 3-year, $27 million contract extension with Toronto.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/dailypitch/post/2012/07/encarnacion-sticking-around-toronto-with-new-contract/1#.T__5JfVgFQ4|title=Encarnacion sticking around Toronto with new contract|last=Barzilai|first=Peter|date=July 12, 2012|accessdate=July 13, 2012|work=USA Today}}</ref> The deal included a $10 million club option for the 2016 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120712&content_id=34857644&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor|title=Blue Jays sign Edwin Encarnacion to three-year contract extension|last=Toman|first=Chris|date=July 12, 2012|accessdate=July 13, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718233015/http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120712&content_id=34857644&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor|archive-date=July 18, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn September 13, 2012, in a home game against the Seattle Mariners, Encarnaci\u00f3n hit his 40th home run of the season (off starter [[F\u00e9lix Hern\u00e1ndez]]), and recorded his 100th RBI of the season, marking the first time in his career that he had surpassed 40 home runs and 100 RBIs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2012_09_13_seamlb_tormlb_1&mode=recap&c_id=tor|title=Encarnacion belts No. 40 as Blue Jays pound King Felix|work=MLB.com|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|date=September 13, 2012|accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n was unanimously named by the Baseball Writers' Association of America (BBWAA) as the [[Neil MacCarl Award|Blue Jays Player of the Year]] on November 28, 2012. He also received the Most Improved Player award for the Jays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20121128&content_id=40445640&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor|title=Edwin Encarnacion named Blue Jays top player by BBWAA|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=November 28, 2012|accessdate=November 28, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121201150022/http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20121128&content_id=40445640&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor|archive-date=December 1, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n July 2013.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Encarnaci\u00f3n in 2013]]\nOn May 23, 2013, Encarnaci\u00f3n hit his fifth career grand slam to give the Blue Jays an 8\u20133 lead over the [[Baltimore Orioles]]. The Jays would win the game 12\u20136.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2013_05_23_balmlb_tormlb_1&mode=recap_home&c_id=tor|title=Encarnacion's slam punctuates batting showcase|last=Peaslee|first=Evan|publisher=MLB.com|date=May 24, 2013|accessdate=May 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn July 6, 2013, Encarnaci\u00f3n was named to his first all-star game as a reserve designated hitter for the American League. Encarnaci\u00f3n was one of four Blue Jays to be named, the others being Jos\u00e9 Bautista, [[Brett Cecil]], and [[Steve Delabar]]. Up to the All-Star break, Encarnaci\u00f3n posted a triple-slash of .264/.353/.532 with 25 home runs and 72 RBIs. In the All-Star Game, Encarnaci\u00f3n entered as a pinch-hitter for [[David Ortiz]] in the seventh inning, and finished the game 0\u20132. In a game against the [[Houston Astros]] on July 26, 2013, Encarnaci\u00f3n became only the second Blue Jay in franchise history to hit two home runs in one inning, joining [[Joe Carter]] who did so on October 3, 1993 \u2013 tying the Major League record for most home runs in an inning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=330726114&teams=houston-astros-vs-toronto-blue-jays|title=Jays' Edwin Encarnacion hits 2 HRs in 8-run 7th inning uprising|date=July 26, 2013|publisher=espn.com|accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/recbooks/rb_hr10.shtml|title=Most Home Run in an Inning Records|date=|publisher=baseball-almanac.com|accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref> Leading off the 7th inning behind at 6\u20134, Encarnaci\u00f3n hit a solo home run and would later hit his sixth career grand slam, receiving a [[curtain call]] afterwards as the Blue Jays would score 8 runs in the inning and lead 12\u20136.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2013_07_26_houmlb_tormlb_1&mode=recap_home&c_id=tor|title=Encarnacion, Reyes power Blue Jays' outburst|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|publisher=MLB.com|date=July 27, 2013|accessdate=July 27, 2013}}</ref> He was named the American League Player of the Week on July 29, after batting .520 with three doubles, two home runs, and eight RBIs over the prior week.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/baseball/blue-jays-edwin-encarnacion-named-al-player-of-the-week/article13482931/|title=Blue Jays' Edwin Encarnacion named AL player of the week|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]|date=July 29, 2013|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n hit his 30th home run of the season on August 7, 2013, against the Seattle Mariners. In doing so, he recorded back-to-back 30 home run seasons for the first time in his career. Playing against the [[Kansas City Royals]] on August 31, 2013, Encarnaci\u00f3n recorded his 1,000th career hit, a single off Kansas City starter [[Jeremy Guthrie]]. On September 2, he reached 100 RBIs for the second consecutive season on a two-run home run against [[Brandon McCarthy]] of the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]]. He spent time on the bench in mid September with a wrist injury, but made a brief comeback before being placed on the disabled list on September 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/bluejays/2013/09/17/blue_jays_shut_down_edwin_encarnacion_and_brett_cecil.html|title=Blue Jays shut down Edwin Encarnacion and Brett Cecil|last=Kennedy|first=Brendan|publisher=thestar.com|date=September 17, 2013|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref> He underwent successful surgery on September 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/jays-encarnacion-has-successful-wrist-surgery/|title=Jays' Encarnacion has successful wrist surgery|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]|date=September 19, 2013|accessdate=September 19, 2013}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n finished the 2013 season with a .272 average, 36 home runs, and 104 RBIs. He finished with more walks than strikeouts for the first time in his career, with 82 and 62 respectively.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\n====2014\u20132016====\nEncarnaci\u00f3n hit his 200th career home run on May 8, 2014, against [[A. J. Burnett]] of the [[Philadelphia Phillies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article/mlb/helping-to-key-blue-jays-offence-edwin-encarnacion-hits-200th-hr?ymd=20140508&content_id=74820452&vkey=news_mlb|title=Helping to key offence, Encarnacion hits 200th HR|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=May 8, 2014|accessdate=May 8, 2014}}</ref> On May 12, he was named the American League Player of the Week for May 5\u201311, when he recorded a league-leading four home runs and 10 RBIs, and batted .321.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=451982|title=Blue Jays' Encarnacion named AL Player of the Week|work=TSN.ca|date=May 12, 2014|accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n continued his hot hitting in May by becoming the first player in Blue Jays franchise history to have 4 multi home run games in a month, and the first player in the majors to do so since [[Troy Tulowitzki]] in September 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?c_id=tor&gid=2014_05_21_tormlb_bosmlb_1&mode=recap_away&partnerId=as_mlb_20140522_24425944|title=Encarnacion's 2nd straight 2-HR game lifts Blue Jays|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=May 21, 2014|accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> On May 26 he established a new club record for home runs in May by hitting his 13th off of [[\u00c1lex Colom\u00e9]] of the [[Tampa Bay Rays]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2014_05_26_tbamlb_tormlb_1&mode=recap_home&c_id=tor|title=Blue Jays rout Rays with 16 hits, three homers|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=May 26, 2014|accessdate=May 26, 2014}}</ref> The following day, Encarnaci\u00f3n tied the team record for home runs in any month of the season, when he hit his 14th to help the Blue Jays extend their winning streak to 8 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article/mlb/blue-jays-first-baseman-edwin-encarnacion-ties-club-record-with-14th-homer-in-a-month?ymd=20140527&content_id=77067720&vkey=news_mlb|title=Edwin ties club record with 14th homer in a month|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=May 27, 2014|accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn May 29, in a home game against the [[Kansas City Royals]], Encarnaci\u00f3n hit two home runs for a total of 18 on the season and 16 in the month of May, giving him the Blue Jays franchise record for home runs in any month of the regular season. He also tied [[Mickey Mantle]] for the American League record for home runs in May.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article/mlb/blue-jays-slugger-edwin-encarnacion-ties-mickey-mantle-for-most-american-league-homers-hit-in-may?ymd=20140529&content_id=77398728&vkey=news_mlb|title=Encarnacion ties Mantle for most AL homers in May|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=May 29, 2014|accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref> He was unanimously selected as the Blue Jays Player of the Month by the Toronto chapter of the BBWAA on June 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20140602&content_id=77864090&vkey=pr_tor&c_id=tor|title=Encarnacion named Honda Player of the Month|work=MLB.com|date=June 2, 2014|accessdate=June 2, 2014}}</ref> A day later he was named the [[Major League Baseball Player of the Month|AL Player of the Month]] of May by MLB.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20140603&content_id=78018698&vkey=pr_mlb&c_id=mlb|title=Edwin Encarnacion of the Toronto Blue Jays named the American League Player of the Month for May|work=MLB.com|date=June 3, 2014|accessdate=June 3, 2014}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n hit two 3-run home runs in a win over the Cincinnati Reds on June 20. His 6 RBIs were a key contribution in helping the Blue Jays to their second-largest comeback victory in franchise history, being down 8\u20130 after the second inning and going on to win 14\u20139.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2014_06_20_tormlb_cinmlb_1&mode=recap_away&c_id=tor|title=Encarnacion leads Blue Jays' epic comeback|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=June 20, 2014|accessdate=June 20, 2014}}</ref> In total for 2014, Encarnaci\u00f3n batted .268 with 34 home runs and 98 RBIs.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\nOn June 30, 2015, Encarnaci\u00f3n earned 10-and-5 rights by having at least 10 years of service time in the big-leagues, with the last 5 being on the same team. These rights give Encarnaci\u00f3n the ability to veto any trade he would be involved in.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/against-the-odds-encarnacion-hits-special-milestone/|title=Against the odds, Encarnacion hits special milestone|last=Davidi|first=Shi|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=June 30, 2015|accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> He joined fellow Blue Jay Jos\u00e9 Bautista on the list of active players to hold this distinction.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.vice.com/en_us/article/allowing-bautista-encarnacion-to-acquire-veto-rights-shows-blue-jays-have-no-desire-to-trade-them|title=Allowing Bautista, Encarnacion to acquire veto rights shows the Blue Jays have no desire to trade them|work=sports.vice.com|date=June 11, 2015|accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n hit his 250th career home run on August 6, in a 9\u20133 win over the Minnesota Twins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/baseball/mlb/edwin-encarnacion-blue-jays-bats-make-twins-pay-in-series-finale-1.3182242|title=Edwin Encarnacion, Blue Jays' bats make Twins pay in series finale|last=Whyno|first=Stephen|work=cbc.ca|date=August 6, 2015|accessdate=August 6, 2015}}</ref> In an 8\u20135 win over the Philadelphia Phillies on August 18, Encarnaci\u00f3n surpassed [[Jesse Barfield]] on the Blue Jays' all-time home run list, hitting his 180th home run with the franchise. He also extended his hitting streak to a career-high 15 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fantasynews.cbssports.com/fantasybaseball/update/25273999/blue-jays-edwin-encarnacion-hits-in-15th-straight|title=Blue Jays' Edwin Encarnacion hits in 15th straight|last=Krest|first=Shawn|work=fantasynews.cbssports.com|date=August 18, 2015|accessdate=August 18, 2015}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n extended his hitting streak to 24 games on August 29, hitting 3 home runs against the [[Detroit Tigers]], including his third grand slam of the season, and tied [[Roy Howell]]'s franchise record with nine RBIs in a single game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/146101440|title=Encarnacion homers three times, extends hit streak to 24|last=Ross|first=Jamie|work=MLB.com|date=August 29, 2015|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/baseball/mlb/edwin-encarnacion-hits-3-homers-in-blue-jays-rout-of-tigers-1.3208608|title=Edwin Encarnacion hits 3 homers in Blue Jays' rout of Tigers|last=Whyno|first=Stephen|work=cbc.ca|date=August 29, 2015|accessdate=August 29, 2015}}</ref> The following day, Encarnaci\u00f3n broke the franchise record for RBIs in a single month, when he hit a solo home run to give him 35 RBIs in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/146275574|title=Encore-nacion: Homer extends streak to 25|last=Ross|first=Jamie|work=MLB.com|date=August 30, 2015|accessdate=August 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-encarnacion-extend-hitting-streak-sets-new-record/|title=Blue Jays' Encarnacion extends hitting streak, sets new record|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=August 30, 2015|accessdate=August 30, 2015}}</ref> He was named the American League Player of the Week on August 31, after batting .391 with 6 home runs and 17 RBIs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/146492008|title=Edwin Encarnacion of the Toronto Blue Jays named American League Player of the Week|work=MLB.com|date=August 31, 2015|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref> On September 2, Encarnaci\u00f3n won the American League Player of the Month award for the second time in his career, after batting .407 with 11 home runs and 35 RBIs in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MLB/status/639173111691083776|title=MLB on Twitter|work=Twitter|date=September 2, 2015|accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref> \n\nHe finished the 2015 regular season with a .277 batting average, 39 home runs, and 111 RBIs.<ref name=\"BR\"/> Encarnaci\u00f3n played in all 5 games of the [[2015 American League Division Series]], and batted .333 with one home run and 3 RBIs. In the [[2015 American League Championship Series|American League Championship Series]], he hit .227 with two RBIs in 6 games.<ref name=\"BR\"/> On October 27, Encarnaci\u00f3n underwent successful [[Athletic pubalgia|sports hernia]] surgery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-slugger-encarnacion-undergoes-sports-hernia-surgery/|title=Blue Jays slugger Encarnacion undergoes sports hernia surgery|last=Davidi|first=Shi|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=October 27, 2015|accessdate=October 27, 2015}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n's $10 million option for 2016 was exercised by the Blue Jays on November 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-exercise-options-on-bautista-dickey-encarnacion/|title=Blue Jays exercise options on Bautista, Dickey, Encarnacion|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=November 3, 2015|accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n 2016 Opening Day.jpg|thumb|left|Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n in 2016 Opening Day]]\nPrior to 2016 spring training, Encarnaci\u00f3n set an Opening Day deadline to negotiate a contract extension with the Blue Jays. He suffered an oblique injury early in the spring, and as a result did not participate in any Major League games. In addition, contract extension negotiations ended early, when both sides could not agree on the terms of the contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/bluejays/2016/04/04/blue-jays-edwin-encarnacion-end-extension-talks.html|title=Blue Jays, Edwin Encarnacion end extension talks|last=Kennedy|first=Brendan|work=thestar.com|date=April 4, 2016|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref> On April 26, Encarnaci\u00f3n hit his 200th home run as a member of the Blue Jays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/encarnacion-continues-ascent-blue-jays-home-run-ranks/|title=Encarnacion continues ascent of Blue Jays' home run ranks|last=Davidi|first=Shi|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=April 27, 2016|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n hit his fourth walk-off home run as a Blue Jay on June 10, defeating the Baltimore Orioles 4\u20133 in the tenth inning. In doing so, he became the Blue Jays all-time leader in walk-off home runs as well as the eighth player in franchise history to reach 600 RBI.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/encarnacion-gives-blue-jays-another-moment-cherish/|title=Encarnacion gives Blue Jays another moment to cherish|last=Blair|first=Jeff|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=June 10, 2016|accessdate=June 10, 2016}}</ref> In the first inning of a game on [[Canada Day|July 1]], Encarnaci\u00f3n was ejected by home plate umpire [[Vic Carapazza]] for arguing balls and strikes. He made contact with Carapazza after being ejected, and on July 3, was given a one-game suspension.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-encarnacion-suspended-one-game-bumping-umpire/|title=Blue Jays' Encarnacion suspended one game for bumping umpire|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=July 3, 2016|accessdate=July 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/teams/toronto-blue-jays/blue-jays-encarnacion-drops-appeal-serves-one-game-suspension/|title=Blue Jays' Encarnacion drops appeal, serves one-game suspension|last=Ashbourne|first=Nick|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=July 10, 2016|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> On August 12, Encarnaci\u00f3n hit the 300th home run of his career, joining [[Joe Carter]], [[Carlos Delgado]], and teammate Jos\u00e9 Bautista as the only players to hit their 300th home run with the Blue Jays franchise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/195237516/edwin-encarnacion-hits-his-300th-career-hr/|title=Encarnacion clubs his 300th career home run|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=August 12, 2016|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n recorded his 100th RBI of the season in a 12\u20136 win over the [[New York Yankees]] on August 16, becoming the first player to reach the milestone in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/196060940/edwin-encarnacion-first-to-100-rbis/|title=3-RBI night puts Encarnacion 1st to 100 RBIs|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=August 17, 2016|accessdate=August 17, 2016}}</ref> On September 16, he hit his 40th home run of the season, and joined Jos\u00e9 Bautista and Carlos Delgado as the only Blue Jays with multiple 40-homer seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/tulowitzki-encarnacion-slug-blue-jays-win-angels/|title=Tulowitzki, Encarnacion slug Blue Jays to win over Angels|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=September 17, 2016|accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the eleventh inning of the [[2016 American League Wild Card Game|2016 Wild Card game]], Encarnaci\u00f3n hit a walk-off, three-run home run to give the Blue Jays a 5\u20132 victory and send them to the [[2016 American League Division Series|American League Division Series]] to face the Texas Rangers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-defeat-orioles-al-wild-card-game/|title=Encarnacion walk-off lifts Blue Jays over Orioles in AL wild-card game|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=October 4, 2016|accessdate=October 4, 2016}}</ref> On November 7, the Blue Jays extended a $17.2 million qualifying offer to Encarnaci\u00f3n,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-extend-qualifying-offers-encarnacion-bautista/|title=Blue Jays extend qualifying offers to Encarnacion, Bautista|last=Davidi|first=Shi|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=November 7, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2016}}</ref> which he declined on November 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/208848218/edwin-encarnacion-jose-bautista-free-agents/|title=Encarnacion, Bautista reject qualifying offers|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=November 14, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Cleveland Indians===\n[[File:Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n 2017 vs. Orioles.jpg|thumb|Encarnaci\u00f3n with the Indians]]\nOn January 5, 2017, Encarnaci\u00f3n signed a three-year contract with the [[Cleveland Indians]] worth $60 million.<ref>{{cite web|title=Indians sign free agent Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n to a three-year contract|url=http://m.indians.mlb.com/news/article/212729276/indians-introduce-edwin-encarnacion/|accessdate=January 5, 2017 |first=Jordan |last=Bastian |work=mlb.com |date=January 5, 2017}}</ref> The deal included a club option for the 2020 season worth an additional $25 million, with a $5 million [[buyout]] clause.\nOn Opening Day, he hit a home run against the Texas Rangers. On July 25, 2017, in the first game of a series against the [[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim]], Encarnaci\u00f3n hit a walk-off grand slam in the bottom of the 11th inning, winning the game 11-7 for the Indians. In his first season with the Indians, he hit .258 with 38 home runs and 107 RBIs. He also drew a career high 104 walks.\n\nOn August 12, 2018, Encarnaci\u00f3n was placed on the disabled list with a hand contusion, his second stint on the disabled list in the season.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.mlb.com/indians/news/edwin-encarnacion-goes-on-disabled-list/c-289893662 | title=Hand contusion lands Edwin on disabled list}}</ref> He finished the season with 32 home runs and 107 RBIs, his seventh consecutive season of over 30 home runs and his fourth consecutive season of 100 or more RBIs. However, he batted .246.\n\n===Seattle Mariners===\nOn December 13, 2018, the Indians traded Encarnaci\u00f3n to the [[Seattle Mariners]] in a three-team trade with the [[Tampa Bay Rays]] which sent [[Carlos Santana (baseball)|Carlos Santana]] to the Indians, with the Indians also acquiring [[Jake Bauers]] from the Rays, with the Rays getting [[Yandy D\u00edaz]] and [[Cole Sulser]].<ref>{{cite web|last=|first=|url=https://marinersblog.mlblogs.com/mariners-acquire-1b-dh-edwin-encarnaci%C3%B3n-and-compensatory-round-b-pick-from-indians-7b50a5260876?sf96357322=1|title=Mariners Acquire 1B/DH Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n and Compensatory Round B Pick from Indians |publisher=mariners.mlb.com |date=December 13, 2018 |accessdate=December 13, 2018}}</ref> Encarnaci\u00f3n hit his first home run as a member of the Seattle Mariners on March 28, 2019. In 65 games with the Mariners through mid-June, Encarnaci\u00f3n batted .241 with 21 home runs and 49 RBIs.\n\n===New York Yankees===\n[[File:Encarnacion 2019.jpg|thumb|Encarnaci\u00f3n with the Yankees in 2019]]\nOn June 15, 2019, the Mariners traded Encarnaci\u00f3n to the [[New York Yankees]] in exchange for minor league pitcher Juan Then and cash considerations.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/edwin-encarnacion-trade-yankees |title=Yanks acquire Encarnacion from M's |first=Russell |last=Dorsey |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=June 16, 2019 |accessdate=June 16, 2019}}</ref> On August 3, Encarnaci\u00f3n was hit by a pitch; he left the game with a fractured right wrist, and was placed on the 10-day injured list later that day. On October 31, 2019, the New York Yankees announced they would not be exercising their club option for Encarnaci\u00f3n for 2020, allowing him to enter the 2019-2020 free agent market.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/players/playerpage/392294/edwin-encarnacion |title = Edwin Encarnacion, DH, New York Yankees}}</ref>\n\n===Chicago White Sox=== \nOn January 9, 2020, Encarnacion signed a 1-year deal with the White Sox.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/edwin-encarnacion-signs-with-white-sox|title=White Sox announce deal with Encarnacion|date=January 9, 2020|accessdate=January 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Baseball|Dominican Republic}}\n*[[List of Major League Baseball career home run leaders]]\n*[[List of Toronto Blue Jays home run leaders]]\n*[[List of Toronto Blue Jays team records]]\n*[[Major League Baseball Player of the Week Award]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=429665|espn=5904|br=e/encared01|fangraphs=2151|brm=encarn001edw|retro=E/Pencae001}}\n* {{twitter}}\n* {{instagram|encadwin|Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n}}\n\n{{AL RBI champions}}\n{{Dominican Republic roster 2013 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{2013 World Baseball Classic All WBC Team}}\n{{Chicago White Sox roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Encarnacion, Edwin}}\n\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:\u00c1guilas Cibae\u00f1as players]]\n[[Category:All-Star Futures Game players]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:American League RBI champions]]\n[[Category:Billings Mustangs players]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Chattanooga Lookouts players]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Reds players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Indians players]]\n[[Category:Dayton Dragons players]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic expatriate baseball players in Canada]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic expatriate baseball players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic expatriates in Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Dunedin Blue Jays players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Rangers players]]\n[[C