          = \n| status            = \n| closed            = \n| students          = \n| sixth_form_students = \n| pupils            = Upper School: 344<br>Lower School: 139\n| alumni            = \n| nobel_laureates   = \n| enrollment        =\n| gradeK            = \n| grade1            = \n| grade2            = \n| grade3            = \n| grade4            = \n| grade5            = \n| grade6            = \n| grade7            = \n| grade8            = \n| grade9            = \n| grade10           = \n| grade11           = \n| grade12           = \n| grade13           = \n| other_grade_label = \n| other             = \n| communities       = \n| feeder_schools           = \n| free_label        = \n| free_text         = \n| free_label1       = \n| free_text1        = \n| free_label2       = \n| free_text2        = \n| free_label3       = \n| free_text3        = \n| free_label4       = \n| free_text4        = \n| free_label5       = \n| free_text5        = \n| footnotes         = \n| picture           = \n| homepage          = {{url|ross.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Ross School''' is a private school K-12 school located on 63 acres in the [[East Hampton (town), New York|Town of East Hampton]], on [[Long Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ross School |url=http://www.admissionsquest.com/cfm_public/pg_schlinfo2.cfm/schlid/1052/school/ross-school |website=admissionsquest |publisher=admissionsquest |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref> Named after her late husband [[Steven J. Ross]], the school was founded in 1991 by Courtney Sale Ross as a day school for their daughter Nicole and several of her friends.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Eaton |first1=Phoebe |title=The Continuing Education of Mrs. Ross |url=https://nymag.com/news/features/29724/ |publisher=New York Magazine |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref> The original pre-nursery, nursery, and pre-kindergarten programs were discontinued in September 2020<ref>{{cite web |last1=Garrison |first1=Virginia |title=Ross School To End Programs For Youngest Students |url=https://www.27east.com/east-hampton-press/ross-school-to-end-programs-for-youngest-students-1669510/ |publisher=East Hampton Press |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>. Ross School transitioned to a boarding school in 2010 after its founder discontinued private funding. Students in grades 6-12 may board five days per week or full-time. The school has supplemented its budget by catering breakfast and lunch from its innovative Caf\u00e9 to the Bridgehampton public schools and offering culinary arts and landscaping classes to East Hampton high school students.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tilghman |first1=Nancy |title=Ross School's Cutbacks Set Off Shock Waves |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/15/nyregion/ross-school-s-cutbacks-set-off-shock-waves.html |website=New York Times |publisher=New York Times |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nA majority of the student body is international, with the highest-represented nations including Brazil, China, Japan, and Mexico. Head of School Bill O'Hearn has served in similar positions at the [[Beijing City International School]] in China and the [[Aga Khan Academy]] in Mombasa, Kenya.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sampson |first1=Christine |title=Former Head of School Returns to Ross |url=https://www.easthamptonstar.com/2019815/former-head-school-returns-ross |publisher=The East Hampton Star |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Curriculum==\nRoss School's curriculum is based on world cultural history and the evolution of consciousness and reflects the collaborative work of its founding mentors, mathematician [[Ralph Abraham (mathematician)|Ralph Abraham]] and cultural historian [[William Irwin Thompson]]. Cultural history is integrated with other academic subjects, such as language arts, math, and science, at every grade level.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Delatiner |first1=Barbara |title=A Garden of Learning, Growing Like a Weed?; The Ross School Discovers That Gobs of Money and Good Intentions Can't Buy Unopposed Expansion |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/30/nyregion/garden-learning-growing-like-weed-ross-school-discovers-that-gobs-money-good.html?login=smartlock&auth=login-smartlock |publisher=New York Times |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=New Way to Learn at The Ross School in New York |url=https://www.marthastewartweddings.com/340652/new-way-learn-ross-school-new-york |website=Martha Stewart |publisher=Martha Stewart |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref> Field Academy takes place during a three-week period between the school's winter and spring terms. Students and teachers travel and work on intensive projects and courses covering an array of subjects at home and across the world.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Finn |first1=Lisa |title=Ross School Students Head Off on 'Field Academy', Focusing on Sustainability at Home and Abroad |url=https://patch.com/new-york/easthampton/ross-school-students-head-field-academy-focusing-sustainability-home-abroad |website=Patch |publisher=Patch |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref> present a capstone project that symbolizes the culmination of their journey through the curriculum and integrates the Ross School principles of multiple intelligences, cultural/historical context, personal reflection, application of technology, and pursuit of excellence.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Finn |first1=LIsa |title=Ross School's 2016 Senior Project Exhibition Kicks Off in East Hampton |url=https://patch.com/new-york/easthampton/ross-schools-2016-senior-project-exhibition-kicks-east-hampton |website=Patch |publisher=Patch |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref> Since August 2016, The Montauk Observatory's 20\" Meade RCX 400 telescope has been housed at the Ross School, where students and stargazers gather for viewing and free astronomy lectures.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Vespe |first1=Elizabeth |title=Montauk Observatory Gives New Telescope A Test Run At New Ross School Location |url=https://www.27east.com/southampton-press/montauk-observatory-gives-new-telescope-a-test-run-at-new-ross-school-location-1593291/ |website=Southampton Press |publisher=Southampton Press |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Giustino |first1=Ken |title=At The Montauk Observatory |url=https://www.montauksun.com/at-the-montauk-observatory-6/ |website=Montauk Sun |publisher=Montauk Sun |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\nIn 2018, the Ross School achieved the founder's original vision by closing its five-building Lower School location in Bridgehampton and moving the early childhood and elementary grades to the Upper School campus in East Hampton. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Sampson |first1=Christine |title=Ross School Will Consolidate Lower School, Upper School Campuses |url=https://sagharborexpress.com/ross-school-will-consolidate-lower-school-upper-school-campuses/ |publisher=Sag Harbor Express |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ross School To Close Bridgehampton Campus, Will Move Lower School Students To Goodfriend Drive |url=https://www.27east.com/southampton-press/ross-school-to-close-bridgehampton-campus-will-move-lower-school-students-to-goodfriend-drive-1429490/ |publisher=Southampton Press |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, the school proposed a 50-building, {{Convert|600000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} expansion to its {{Convert|140|acre|km2|adj=on}} campus which would have made it one of the biggest complexes in the Hamptons.  Enraged environmentalists charged that Courtney Ross was polluting the debate by paying to protest proposed expansion of the [[Long Island Central Pine Barrens]] protections into East Hampton.<ref>[http://www.pinebarrens.org/pdfs/Newsletters/spring00.pdf Largest Project Ever Proposed for South Fork - The Pine Line - Spring/Summer 2000]</ref>  The school eventually backed down on the expansion and in 2006 the same critics of this expansion were to applaud its \"green\" initiatives.\n\n== Summer events and programs==\nThe Ross School hosts an Annual Starlight Ball in June which has featured [[Aretha Franklin]], the [[Jonas Brothers]], [[Martha Stewart]], [[Cyndi Lauper]] and \u201cSaturday Night Live\u2019s\u201d [[Seth Meyers]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Seay |first1=Kendra |title=The Annual Club Starlight Ball For Ross School In East Hampton |url=https://guestofaguest.com/hamptons/events/the-annual-club-starlight-ball-for-ross-school-in-east-hampton |publisher=guestofaguest.com |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref> The largest event to date was held in 2007: a series of five musical concerts entitled \"Social @ Ross\" with [[Prince (musician)|Prince]]; [[Dave Matthews]] and [[Tim Reynolds]]; [[Billy Joel]]; [[James Taylor]] and [[Tom Petty]] and the Heartbreakers. The price of a ticket to the series was $15,000.<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/story?id=3371477&page=1&CMP=OTC-RSSFeeds0312 Only in the Hamptons: a $15,000 Rock Concert Rich and Famous Drop $15,000 for Five-Act Concert Series]</ref>\n\nSummer programs offered by the Ross School include College Prep, English as a second language, marine science, design, Mandarin immersion, engineering, mathematics, and tennis.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ross School - Summer Term |url=https://www.teenlife.com/summer-program/ross-school-ross-summer-term/ |website=teenlife.com |publisher=teenlife.com |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Ross Institute==\nIn 1996, Courtney Sale Ross founded Ross Institute for Advanced Study and Innovation in Education. The Institute provides training and certification for teachers interested in establishing schools based on the Ross School model.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ross Institute |url=https://vimeo.com/rossinstitute/about |website=Vimeo |publisher=Vimeo |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref> Universities and organizations that have worked with the Institute include Harvard's Graduate School of Education; NYU's Steinhardt School of Culture, Education, and Human Development; University of Southern California; Smithsonian Institution, Moorea Biocode Project, Moorea IDEA, and the National Geographic Society.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ross Institute |url=https://www.rossinstitute.org/about |website=rossinstitute.org |publisher=rossinstitute.org |accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n;Alumni\n*[[Alexa Ray Joel]], singer\n*[[Scott Disick]], reality television star\n*[[Victoria de Lesseps]], artist\n*[[Tessa Gr\u00e4fin von Walderdorff]], socialite\n*The grandchildren of [[Dame Julie Andrews]] (Hope Hamilton and Sam Hamilton)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ross.org Official page]\n* [http://rossinstitute.org/ Ross Institute]\n* [http://summercamp.ross.org/ Ross School Summer Camp]\n* [http://www.boardingschools.com/school-profile/Ross-School The Association of Boarding Schools profile]\n\n[[Category:Private high schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:East Hampton (town), New York]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Schools in Suffolk County, New York]]\n", "name_user": "Margaretwmiller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCurriculum", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ross_School_(East_Hampton,_New_York)"}
{"title_page": "Substituted amphetamine", "text_new": "{{short description|Class of compounds based upon the amphetamine structure}}\n{{redirect|Amphetamines|the chemical|Amphetamine||Amphetamine (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{infobox drug class\n| Image    = Racemic amphetamine.svg\n| Alt      = Racemic amphetamine skeleton\n| Caption = [[Racemic amphetamine]] skeleton\n| Chemical_class = Substituted derivatives of amphetamine\n}}\n{| class=\"infobox\"\n|+ [[Chirality (chemistry)|Optical isomers]] of [[amphetamine]] \n|-\n|[[File:L-amphetamine.svg|100px]]||[[File:D-amphetamine.svg|100px]]\n|-\n|[[File:L-amphetamine-3D-vdW.png|100px]]||[[File:D-amphetamine-3D-vdW.png|100px]]\n|-\n|[[Levoamphetamine|L-amphetamine]]||[[Dextroamphetamine|D-amphetamine]]\n|}\n'''Substituted amphetamines''' are a [[chemical class|class of compounds]] based upon the [[amphetamine]] structure;<ref name=\"Amphetamine - a substituted amphetamine\" /> it includes all [[derivative (chemistry)|derivative]] compounds which are formed by replacing, or [[substitution reaction|substituting]], one or more [[hydrogen atom]]s in the amphetamine core structure with [[substituent]]s.<ref name=\"Amphetamine - a substituted amphetamine\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hagel JM, Krizevski R, Marsolais F, Lewinsohn E, Facchini PJ | title = Biosynthesis of amphetamine analogs in plants | journal = Trends Plant Sci. | volume = 17 | issue = 7 | pages = 404\u2013412 | date = 2012 | pmid = 22502775 | doi = 10.1016/j.tplants.2012.03.004 | quote = Substituted amphetamines, which are also called phenylpropylamino alkaloids, are a diverse group of nitrogen-containing compounds that feature a phenethylamine backbone with a methyl group at the \u03b1-position relative to the nitrogen (Figure 1). Countless variation in functional group substitutions has yielded a collection of synthetic drugs with diverse pharmacological properties as stimulants, empathogens and hallucinogens [3].&nbsp;... Beyond (1''R'',2''S'')-ephedrine and (1''S'',2''S'')-pseudoephedrine, myriad other substituted amphetamines have important pharmaceutical applications. The stereochemistry at the \u03b1-carbon is often a key determinant of pharmacological activity, with (''S'')-enantiomers being more potent. For example, (''S'')-amphetamine, commonly known as d-amphetamine or dextroamphetamine, displays five times greater psychostimulant activity compared with its (''R'')-isomer [78]. Most such molecules are produced exclusively through chemical syntheses and many are prescribed widely in modern medicine. For example, (''S'')-amphetamine (Figure 4b), a key ingredient in Adderall<sup>&reg;</sup> and Dexedrine<sup>&reg;</sup>, is used to treat attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) [79].&nbsp;... <br />[Figure 4](b) Examples of synthetic, pharmaceutically important substituted amphetamines.}}</ref><ref name=\"Substituted amphetamines\">{{cite book | author = Glennon RA |veditors=Lemke TL, Williams DA, Roche VF, Zito W | title=Foye's principles of medicinal chemistry | date=2013 | publisher=Wolters Kluwer Health/Lippincott Williams & Wilkins | location=Philadelphia, USA | isbn=9781609133450 | pages=646\u2013648 | edition=7th | section-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Sd6ot9ul-bUC&pg=PA646&q=substituted%20derivatives%20substituents%20amphetamine%20substitution#v=onepage | accessdate=| section=Phenylisopropylamine stimulants: amphetamine-related agents | quote = The simplest unsubstituted phenylisopropylamine, 1-phenyl-2-aminopropane, or amphetamine, serves as a common structural template for hallucinogens and psychostimulants. Amphetamine produces central stimulant, anorectic, and sympathomimetic actions, and it is the prototype member of this class (39).}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid1855720\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Lillsunde P, Korte T | title = Determination of ring- and N-substituted amphetamines as heptafluorobutyryl derivatives | journal = Forensic Sci. Int. | volume = 49 | issue = 2 | pages = 205\u2013213 | date = March 1991 | pmid = 1855720 | doi=10.1016/0379-0738(91)90081-s}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Custodio|first=Raly James Perez|last2=Botanas|first2=Chrislean Jun|last3=Yoon|first3=Seong Shoon|last4=Pe\u00f1a|first4=June Bryan de la|last5=Pe\u00f1a|first5=Irene Joy dela|last6=Kim|first6=Mikyung|last7=Woo|first7=Taeseon|last8=Seo|first8=Joung-Wook|last9=Jang|first9=Choon-Gon|last10=Kwon|first10=Yong Ho|last11=Kim|first11=Nam Yong|date=2017-11-01|title=Evaluation of the Abuse Potential of Novel Amphetamine Derivatives with Modifications on the Amine (NBNA) and Phenyl (EDA, PMEA, 2-APN) Sites|journal=Biomolecules & Therapeutics|language=en|volume=25|issue=6|pages=578\u2013585|doi=10.4062/biomolther.2017.141|issn=2005-4483|pmc=5685426|pmid=29081089}}</ref> The compounds in this class span a variety of pharmacological subclasses, including [[stimulants]], [[Empathogen-entactogen|empathogens]], and [[hallucinogens]], among others.<ref name=\"Substituted amphetamines\" /> Examples of substituted amphetamines are amphetamine (itself),<ref name=\"Amphetamine - a substituted amphetamine\" /><ref name=\"Substituted amphetamines\" /> [[methamphetamine]],<ref name=\"Amphetamine - a substituted amphetamine\" /> [[ephedrine]],<ref name=\"Amphetamine - a substituted amphetamine\" /> [[cathinone]],<ref name=\"Amphetamine - a substituted amphetamine\" /> [[phentermine]],<ref name=\"Amphetamine - a substituted amphetamine\" /> [[mephentermine]],<ref name=\"Amphetamine - a substituted amphetamine\" /> [[bupropion]],<ref name=\"Amphetamine - a substituted amphetamine\" /> [[methoxyphenamine]],<ref name=\"Amphetamine - a substituted amphetamine\" /> [[selegiline]],<ref name=\"Amphetamine - a substituted amphetamine\" /> [[amfepramone]],<ref name=\"Amphetamine - a substituted amphetamine\" /> [[pyrovalerone]],<ref name=\"Amphetamine - a substituted amphetamine\" /> [[MDMA]] (ecstasy), and [[2,5-dimethoxy-4-methylamphetamine|DOM]] (STP).\n\nSome of amphetamine's substituted [[Derivative (chemistry)|derivatives]] occur in nature, for example in the leaves of ''[[Ephedra (genus)|Ephedra]]'' and [[khat]] plants which have been used by humans for more than 1000 years for their pharmacological effects.<ref name=\"Amphetamine - a substituted amphetamine\" /> Amphetamine was first produced at the end of the 19th century. By the 1930s, [[amphetamine]] and some of its [[Derivative (chemistry)|derivative]] compounds found use as decongestants in the symptomatic treatment of [[cold]]s and also occasionally as psychoactive agents.  Their effects on the [[central nervous system]] are diverse, but can be summarized by three overlapping types of activity: [[psychoanaleptic]], [[Psychedelics, dissociatives and deliriants|hallucinogenic]] and [[Empathogen-entactogen|empathogenic]]. Various substituted amphetamines may cause these actions either separately or in combination.\n\n==Partial list of substituted amphetamines==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Generic or Trivial Name\n! Chemical Name\n! # of Subs\n|-\n| [[Amphetamine]] || \u03b1-Methyl-phenethylamine || 0\n|-\n| [[Methamphetamine]] || ''N''-Methylamphetamine || 1\n|-\n| [[Etilamfetamine|Ethylamphetamine]] || ''N''-Ethylamphetamine || 1\n|-\n| [[Propylamphetamine]] || ''N''-Propylamphetamine || 1\n|-\n| [[Isopropylamphetamine]] || ''N''-''iso''-Propylamphetamine || 1\n|-\n| [[Phentermine]] || \u03b1-Methylamphetamine || 1\n|-\n| [[Phenylpropanolamine]] (PPA) || \u03b2-Hydroxyamphetamine, (1''R'',2''S'')- || 1\n|-\n| [[Cathine]] || \u03b2-Hydroxyamphetamine, (1''S'',2''S'')- || 1\n|-\n| [[Cathinone]] || \u03b2-Ketoamphetamine || 1\n|-\n| [[Ortetamine]] || 2-Methylamphetamine || 1\n|-\n| [[2-Fluoroamphetamine]] (2-FA) || 2-Fluoroamphetamine || 1\n|-\n| [[3-Methylamphetamine]] (3-MA) || 3-Methylamphetamine || 1\n|-\n| [[2-Phenyl-3-aminobutane]] || 2-Phenyl-3-aminobutane || 1\n|-\n| [[3-Fluoroamphetamine]] (3-FA) || 3-Fluoroamphetamine || 1\n|-\n| [[Norfenfluramine]] |